[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language patient-narrative architecture.** Patient-facing regime narratives require per-language infrastructure that goes beyond translation. The path-dependence framing ("this is the next step given how things have gone, and we will reassess next time") is harder to translate well than single-decision framing; the per-language work is correspondingly more demanding. The architecture requires: per-language reading-level scoring (Flesch-Kincaid equivalent for English, appropriate readability metrics for Spanish, Mandarin, and other supported languages); per-language approved-claim language (the clinical-content team curates the vocabulary that is permissible in each language, because literal translations of approved English phrasing often carry different connotations); per-language templated fallback narratives (the deterministic fallback must exist in every supported language before a language goes live); and per-language validator dispatch (the prohibited-language regex set, the required-content rules, and the reading-level thresholds are language-specific). The pattern mirrors Recipe 4.9's multi-language architecture (A10) and extends it to regime-specific path-dependence framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  31, 33[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Step Functions for training and serving orchestration.** Three workflows: a training workflow (trajectory pipeline, sequential causal modeling, OPE, governance review packaging); a serving workflow (recommendation generation at a decision point); a surveillance workflow (regime adherence, outcome surveillance, drift detection, cohort-stratified monitoring). Step Functions provides the per-stage retry, timeout, and DLQ semantics; all executions are logged to S3 and surfaced in the operational dashboards.
