Purpose: Expand consent posture with explicit consent-data-flow pattern, versioning, similar-trajectory-pool consent layer, and revocation handling per expert review A10

[49m[38;5;9m- 1171      [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Patient consent posture.** Dynamic treatment regime recommendations use the patient's longitudinal trajectory data, including prior actions, outcomes, and (in many implementations) similar-trajectory cohorts of other patients. The consent framing should make this explicit: "your care recommendations are informed by your own past care and outcomes and by the patterns observed in similar patients' care; we use this information with care and you can opt out." The institution's existing consent infrastructure typically does not have all of these granularities; expect to extend it. Consent revocation requires a defined data-handling pathway: revoking patients' contributions to training data, re-training without their data on the next cycle, removing them from similar-trajectory retrieval pools.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient consent posture.** Dynamic treatment regime recommendations use the patient's longitudinal trajectory data, including prior actions, outcomes, and (in many implementations) similar-trajectory cohorts of other patients. The consent architecture requires explicit consent capture with versioning: what the patient consented to, when, under which consent-document version, and the scope of consent (training, recommendation generation, similar-trajectory retrieval for other patients). The similar-trajectory-pool consent layer is distinct from the regime-training consent layer: a patient may consent to "use my data to train the regime" but not to "surface my de-identified trajectory as a similar-trajectory example to other clinicians for other patients." Both consent states must be captured, versioned, and enforced independently. Consent-revocation handling requires a defined data-handling pathway: revoking patients' contributions to training data triggers re-training without their data on the next cycle; revoking similar-trajectory consent removes them from the retrieval pool immediately; the audit trail records the consent state at the time of every regime-training run and every recommendation generation, so retrospective consent questions can be answered. The pattern mirrors 4.5 through 4.9's consent-data-flow architecture.
