[49m[38;5;9m- 1181      [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Regime-deprecation and patient-impact handling.** When a regime version is deprecated (replaced by a newer version, retired due to drift, withdrawn after surveillance findings), the patients with active recommendations under the old version need clear handling: re-recommend under the new version at the next decision point, surface the change to the clinician with the rationale, and avoid silent regime swaps. The deprecation policy is part of the change control plan and should be reviewed by the governance committee.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regime-deprecation and patient-impact handling.** When a regime version is deprecated (replaced by a newer version, retired due to drift, withdrawn after surveillance findings), the architecture must handle three concerns explicitly. First, regime-version continuity in the recommendation record: if a patient's decision-point N was served under regime v3.2.1 and decision-point N+1 is served under v3.3.0, both versions must be visible in the audit trail and in the clinician narrative; the clinician should see "the regime has been updated since your last visit; here is the current recommendation under the new version." Second, version-tagged surveillance partitioning: deprecated-regime outcomes must not silently roll forward into the new regime's surveillance metrics; partition surveillance by regime version so the new regime's calibration and outcome tracking starts clean. Third, the patient-impact-communication pattern when a regime is withdrawn for safety reasons: the institutional analog of FDA-mandated post-market action notifications; affected patients' clinicians receive structured notifications explaining the withdrawal, the reason, and the recommended clinical response. The deprecation policy is part of the change control plan and mirrors 4.9's clinical-content versioning pattern (A9).
